We start by extracting and computing key amounts from the data:

1. Debt to Equity Ratio  
 • From the balance sheet, Total Liabilities are not given directly but we can compute them as the difference between Total Liabilities and Owner’s Equity (which here is Total Liabilities and Owner's Equity minus Owner's Equity). That is:  
  Total Liabilities = 14879933.86 – 11824937.81 = 3054996.05  
 • Total Owner’s Equity is 11824937.81.  
 • So, Debt to Equity Ratio = 3054996.05 / 11824937.81 ≈ 0.2583, which we round to 0.26.

2. Net Profit Margin  
 • From the income statement:  
  Net Profit = –1175062.19  
  Total Revenue = 7099920.95  
 • Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100 ≈ (–1175062.19 / 7099920.95) × 100 ≈ –16.54%.

3. Return on Assets (ROA)  
 • Total Assets from the balance sheet = 14879933.86  
 • ROA = (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100 ≈ (–1175062.19 / 14879933.86) × 100 ≈ –7.90%.

4. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
 • The formula uses average Accounts Receivable. From the balance sheet, the beginning Accounts Receivable (2023-12-31) is 0 and the ending is 3558301.64.  
  Average Accounts Receivable = (0 + 3558301.64) / 2 = 1779150.82  
 • Turnover Ratio = Total Revenue / Average Accounts Receivable ≈ 7099920.95 / 1779150.82 ≈ 3.99.

Thus, the final results are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.26",
    "Net Profit Margin": "-16.54%",
    "Return on Assets (ROA)": "-7.90%",
    "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "3.99"
  }
}
